  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 佳 : '
    value: 住
english:
  title: Prayer to the Divine
  author: Kim Bu-sik
  language: eng
  text: The Way that transcends the ordinary Way has endured clear since ancient times. Divine and doubly divine, within it takes form—containing all mysteries, governing all living things. Consider this humble frame, approaching with reverence the great harmony of creation. Having taken possession of a kingdom now for three years, I look back and find no virtuous governance, no legacy of noble conduct. How can I answer the hopes of the Three Spirits? I fear that unjust punishments and excessive rewards have wounded the harmony of heaven and earth. Perhaps the celestial order has strayed from its course, or mountains and stones signal strange portents. The soldiers and people suffer hunger's anxiety, while barbarian tribes scheme to establish their camps—all born of my lack of virtue. How can I rest in my own ease? Though fortune and misfortune cycle without constancy, yet the forms and protocols of supplication stand complete. With reverence I follow the Way's law, keeping the altar pure and sacred. Even the humble waters of shallow streams and mountain rills, if offered with true faith and sincerity, shall reach the divine. Will heaven's heart and earth's intention refuse to respond to such devotion? I beseech the sublime spirits to bestow their wondrous care, to cast wide their luminous rays—sweeping away all calamities and adding blessing and auspiciousness, granting wealth, longevity, health, and peace as benefit to my people, sparing us from warfare, death, plague, and pestilence as sorrow to our realm. With reverent gaze I look upward to the Holy Spirits; cast down your watchful eye upon us.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Three Spirits' (三靈) refers to Heaven, Earth, and Humanity in Korean Daoist cosmology
  - key: ''
    value: This work was composed during Kim Bu-sik's tenure as King Injong's chief minister, likely as a ritual prayer during a period of natural or political calamity
